  "original_title": "Sri Lanka stocks end week down 2-pct ahead of interim budget",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Sri Lanka stocks end week down 2-pct ahead of interim budget",
      "author": "",
      "body_lines": [
        "ECONOMYNEXT \u2013 Sri Lanka stocks slipped for the fourth consecutive session Friday ending down 2 percent for the week due to continuous selling in index heavy shares, brokers said.",
        "The main All Share Price Index (ASPI) fell 0.39% or 34.69 points to 8,793.39.",
        "\u201cWe saw a lot of selling pressure coming in for margin selling,\u201d an analyst said.",
        "\u201cThere will be selling ahead of the interim budget on August 30.\u201d",
        "The market generated 2.2 billion rupees in turnover, less than this year\u2019s average daily turnover of 3.13 billion rupees.",
        "Friday\u2019s turnover was 2.2 billion rupees, less than the 3.13 billion day average this year.",
        "Sri Lanka defaulted on its foreign debt on April 12 and deepening an economic collapse into political crisis. Sri Lanka is facing its worst fuel and economic crisis in its post-independence era. The economy is expected to contract more than 8 percent this year.",
        "The more liquid S&P SL20 index ended 0.09% or 2.49 points down at 2,863.75.",
        "The main ASPI gained 14.2 percent in August so far after gaining 5.3 percent in July. It lost 9.3 percent in June, 23 percent in April, and 14.5 percent in March.",
        "The index has lost 27.7 percent so far this year after being one of the world\u2019s best stock markets with an 80 percent return last year when large volumes of money were printed.",
        "Net foreign inflow was 405 million rupees on Friday. The total net foreign outflow so far this year is 444 billion rupees.",
        "Investors are also concerned over the steep fall of the rupee from 203 to 370 levels so far in 2022.",
        "Expolanka pushed the index down, closing 2.39 percent weaker at 551.8 rupees a share.",
        "Hayleys closed 2.69 percent down at 97.8 rupees a share, and Royal Ceramics Lanka fell 3.75 percent to 30.8 rupees. (Colombo/Aug26/2022)"
      ],
